US-002 (Accessibility permission bootstrap) is complete. Summary of what landed:

**New code**
- `PermissionsManager.swift` — `@MainActor ObservableObject` wrapping the AX trust state. Live system calls (`AXIsProcessTrusted`, the prompt, opening System Settings) are injected closures with live-impl defaults, so the logic is unit-testable without real permission state or system dialogs. Provides `isTrusted`, a `PermissionStatus` enum (title/detail/symbol), `recheck()`, and `startMonitoring()` (DistributedNotificationCenter `com.apple.accessibility.api` + 1s poll → live pickup without relaunch).
- `AppDelegate.swift` — wired via `@NSApplicationDelegateAdaptor`. On launch it checks trust, prompts if untrusted, and starts monitoring; all of this is **guarded out under XCTest** (the env-var check), so `xcodebuild test` doesn't pop a system permission dialog or hang.
- `PreferencesView.swift` — new Preferences window (⌘, menu item) showing permission status with **Re-check** and **Open System Settings** actions. The menu also shows a "Grant Accessibility Access…" warning while untrusted.

**Tests** — 7 new unit tests (status mapping, recheck pickup, prompt/open-settings invocation, message presence). All 8 tests pass.

**Quality gates** — build `** BUILD SUCCEEDED **`, `swiftlint --strict` 0 violations, tests `** TEST SUCCEEDED **`, and the app launches and stays alive (no crash) whether trusted or not.

**One verification caveat:** I confirmed the app launches stably via CLI, but did not interactively click through the menu → Preferences → Re-check flow (that needs GUI access). The logic is unit-tested; only the visual click-through is unverified.

I did not create a git commit, per the ralph-tui workflow (the engine commits after task completion). Bead `Bringr-93j.2` is closed and learnings are recorded in `.ralph-tui/progress.md`.

